module FloatFieldUnsafe

(* THE MUTANT — and a false proof that would have slipped through a suite that only
   ever put a Float in a PARAMETER.  One field different from 29_floatfield_safe: the
   guard now reads the Float field `f` instead of the Int field `n`.

     match box with | B(f, n) => if f == f then 0 else div(100, d) end

   `f == f` is the same lie as 13_float_unsafe's `x == x`, only now the Float arrived
   through a constructor.  In the logic equality is reflexive — congruence closure
   makes it so, as it must.  At run time `f == f` is FALSE when `f` is NaN, and `main`
   builds exactly that: `B(0.0 / 0.0, 0)`.  So the machine takes the `else` and divides
   100 by 0.

   Were the field speakable, the checker would assume `not (f == f)` in the `else`,
   find it unsatisfiable, and prove the branch VACUOUSLY — `ok: 2 obligation(s) proved`,
   exit 0, then the divide-by-zero.  This is not hypothetical: delete the FLOAT-silence
   guard in `term_opt` (make a Float speakable again) and this file flips from `1 of 2
   unproved` to `2 proved`.  It is 13's regression, guarded on a road 13 does not walk.

   The fix is the same one, and it needs nothing new: a Float has a sort at which no
   term is ever built, so `f` — however it entered — is unnameable, `f == f` is a
   condition the checker cannot read, and an unreadable condition constrains NEITHER
   branch.  The `else`'s division stands with nothing to prove `d != 0`, which is the
   truth: `d` really is 0.

   Expected: 1 of 2 unproved. *)

type Box = | B of Float, Int

fn div(a : Int, b : {v : Int | v != 0}) : Int = a / b

fn get(box : Box, d : Int) : Int =
  match box with
  | B(f, n) => if f == f then 0 else div(100, d)
  end

fn main(io : IO) : IO =
  print(io, show(get(B(0.0 / 0.0, 0), 0)))
